summary: Stephen King’s time traveler tries to undo some painful history.
Stephen King’s latest novel, “11/22/63,” tells of a schoolteacher who travels back to 1958 to alter history, and falls in love as well.
In “Doctor Sleep” Stephen King offers a sequel to “The Shining.”
“Doctor Sleep” picks up the story of Danny, the little boy with psycho-intuitive powers from Stephen King’s 1977 novel “The Shining.”
Stephen King’s lovelorn narrator takes a summer job at a haunted Southern amusement park.
When an enormous transparent dome settles over a small town in Maine in Stephen King’s new novel, it’s just fine with Big Jim, the local tyrant-in-waiting, and his pet goon squad.
“Under the Dome” gravely threatens Stephen King’s status as a mere chart-busting pop cultural phenomenon.
In Stephen King’s “Revival,” a boy is befriended by a charismatic minister with whom he will reconnect in eerie and unsettling ways as an adult.
Two men are locked in a battle of wills in Stephen King’s novel of fanaticism and what might exist on the other side of life.
When Stephen King really wants to put a scare into you, he brings on his most fearsome monster of all, the writer.
Everyday situations became open portals to fantasy and horror in Stephen King’s succinct, fast-moving new collection.
A new short-story collection takes Stephen King back to the form that gave him his seat-of-the-pants start.
Stephen King’s use of horror is not what it used to be. It may still be the impetus for his stories, but it is no longer the foremost reason they’re interesting.
In Stephen King’s new novel, a man recuperating in the Florida Keys begins to paint, with sinister results.
In his new book, Stephen King delivers his version of Joycean wordplay, idiosyncrasy, voluptuousness and stubborn, obsessive chronology.
With one eye on Philip Marlowe, Stephen King takes a crack at the detective novel.

summary: Laura Lippman reviews Stephen King’s “Finders Keepers,” the second entry in a planned trilogy that began with “Mr. Mercedes.”
A retired police detective sees the return of his nemesis in this suspense story with a supernatural twist.
“The Outsider” starts out as a routine police procedural but before long transforms into something much more sinister.
King’s slim new novel, “Elevation,” returns us to Castle Rock, where prejudice drives a plot that blends the fantastical with the mundane.
In his latest, King tells the story of an institution where children with special powers are cultivated — but that’s just where the nightmare begins.
The terror doesn’t come from ghosts or fiends or clowns — it’s ordinary people, folks just like you and me, who are the evil ones.
